Whom should Seahawks hire to replace Pete Carroll? Dan Quinn, Jim Harbaugh and 9 other candidates

By Michael-Shawn Dugar
Jan 10, 2024

RENTON, Wash. — Pete Carroll intended to be the Seattle Seahawks’ head coach next season, and he made his case to stay in that role during his end-of-season meetings with ownership over the last couple of days.

“I wanted to make sure that I stood up for all of our coaches and the players and the things that we had accomplished,” Carroll said during an emotional news conference Wednesday afternoon at the Virginia Mason Athletic Center. “Not so that we could be the coach still, but so that we could continue to have a chance to be successful and keep the organization going. That’s what I was fighting for. In that regard, that was what I was representing in our discussions.

Advertisement

“We got to a good, clean spot where it made sense, and (I) went along with their intentions.”

Instead of running the show for a 15th season, Carroll will watch as general manager John Schneider finally assumes full control of the organization.

GO DEEPER

Pete Carroll not returning as Seahawks coach

“It’s been 14 years and he’s been sitting there waiting for his opportunity, and he deserves it and he’s great at what he does,” Carroll said. “He deserves this moment. I was cheerleading for him. That was the biggest factor … it was to help make sure he could have this opportunity, and he’s going to go for it, and I would do whatever I could to help him be successful.”

Schneider attended Carroll’s news conference but was not made available to the media (team owner Jody Allen was not in attendance). Carroll did not offer specifics on his future role — “We’re going to figure that out,” he said — but made it clear he won’t have input in choosing his successor.

“I’m supporting John,” Carroll said.

Schneider has never hired a head coach, so it’s unclear where he’ll go with the decision. He could try to reunite with someone from Carroll’s coaching tree and maintain some of the cultural and schematic elements that have made Seattle so successful over the last 14 years. Or, Schneider could make a hire that takes the organization in an entirely different direction.

Before we look at some potential candidates, here are notable rules when it comes to coaching hires:

  • To satisfy the Rooney Rule, teams must conduct an in-person interview with at least two external candidates who are people of color and/or women. Virtual interviews don’t satisfy the Rooney Rule requirement.
  • Virtual initial interviews are permitted with candidates employed by another NFL team until Jan. 21. Starting Jan. 22, teams can conduct in-person interviews with candidates employed by other NFL teams whose seasons have ended.
  • Also starting Jan. 22, teams cannot hold initial interviews with candidates employed by teams participating in the AFC and NFC championship games until the end of the employer team’s season. Second interviews are not allowed until Jan. 29.

Now for the candidates.

Ties to the Seahawks

Dan Quinn, Cowboys defensive coordinator

Quinn was Carroll’s defensive line coach in 2010 and later coordinated the championship-winning team in 2013 and the 2014 team that lost the Super Bowl. He then left for the Falcons and took them to the Super Bowl in 2016, losing to the Patriots in overtime. Quinn has been the Cowboys defensive coordinator since 2021, and Dallas’ defense ranks third in expected points added (all stats courtesy of TruMedia unless stated otherwise) during his tenure.

Advertisement

He has already been requested for interviews by the Chargers, Commanders, Panthers and Titans after taking eight interviews for head-coaching jobs over the last two offseasons (five in 2022, three in 2023) before choosing to stay with Dallas. Quinn’s Cowboys host the Packers on Sunday.

Dave Canales, Buccaneers offensive coordinator

Canales followed Carroll from USC to Seattle and wore many hats before leaving for Tampa Bay following the 2022 season. He spent time as the Seahawks’ receivers coach, passing game coordinator and quarterbacks coach (twice) before finally getting a shot to run his own offense.

The Bucs ranked 17th in points per drive and expected points added per play (worse than Seattle in both categories) as they won the NFC South for the third straight year. After bouncing from the Browns to the Panthers and then the Rams, quarterback Baker Mayfield earned the starting job in Tampa Bay and had a productive season. The 2018 No. 1 pick ranked 14th in EPA per dropback — tied with Geno Smith — while having the 10th-highest touchdown rate against the 10th-lowest interception rate.

The Panthers have requested an interview with Canales, whose Bucs host the Eagles on Monday night.

Former head coaches

Steve Wilks, 49ers defensive coordinator

Wilks was the head coach of the Cardinals when they went 3-13 in 2018 with Sam Bradford and Josh Rosen at quarterback. Matt Rhule hired him to be Carolina’s defensive coordinator in 2022, and when Rhule was fired midway through the year, Wilks became interim coach and led the team to a 6-6 record — largely with Sam Darnold at quarterback and without Christian McCaffrey at running back — which included a win over the Seahawks. Many Panthers players campaigned for Wilks to be made the permanent coach (ownership chose Frank Reich, who has since been fired).

Advertisement

Wilks replaced DeMeco Ryans in San Francisco, and his defense gave Seattle — as well as the rest of the league — all kinds of problems this season. The 49ers ranked in the top six in limiting explosive plays, turnovers forced and points per game. They were 12th in EPA per play.

The Chargers have requested to interview Wilks. San Francisco has a bye to start the playoffs.

Leslie Frazier

Frazier was most recently the Bills defensive coordinator from 2017 to 2022. In that span, Buffalo ranked second in explosive play rate, second in EPA per play and third in scoring defense. Frazier, 64, went 21-32-1 as Minnesota’s head coach from 2010 to 2013. Adrian Peterson’s MVP year in 2012 was Frazier’s only winning season (the Vikings were 10-6). It ended with a wild-card loss to the Packers. The Chargers will reportedly interview Frazier on Sunday.

Mike Vrabel

The 48-year-old Vrabel was fired this week after six seasons leading the Tennessee Titans. He posted a record of 54-45 in the regular season and led the Titans to AFC South titles in 2020 and 2021. Tennessee lost to the Ravens in the wild-card round of the 2020 playoffs and got bounced as the No. 1 seed by the Bengals in 2021. Vrabel is 2-3 in the playoffs, with both victories coming in 2019.

The Titans finished with losing records the past two seasons, though Vrabel is expected to be highly coveted during this hiring cycle.

GO DEEPER

Titans fire Vrabel after 6-11 season

Jim Harbaugh, Michigan head coach

Harbaugh had a 44-19-1 record as head coach of the 49ers from 2011 to 2014 and was on the other side of some legendary battles with Carroll’s Seahawks, most notably the 2013 NFC Championship Game that preceded Seattle’s only Super Bowl victory. He won the NFC West twice, went to three conference championship games and narrowly lost the Super Bowl to his brother, the Ravens’ John Harbaugh, in 2012.

Harbaugh, 60, is 89-25 at Michigan and just beat the Washington Huskies in the national championship on Monday. Harbaugh has already been connected to multiple teams and is expected to be highly sought after during this hiring cycle. He’s been a successful head coach at his last three stops (he was at Stanford before joining the 49ers).

GO DEEPER

Where will Bill Belichick, Jim Harbaugh land? NFL execs predict: Sando's Pick Six

Potential first-time coaches (offense)

Eric Bieniemy, Commanders offensive coordinator

Bieniemy, 54, won two championships as the Chiefs offensive coordinator. Kansas City had the best offense in the league during that span (2018-22). In his lone season as the Commanders coordinator, they ranked 25th in points per game and EPA per play. Commanders coach Ron Rivera was fired Monday, and team owner Josh Harris has said they’ll consider Bieniemy as Rivera’s replacement but plan on first hiring a general manager.

Advertisement

While in Kansas City, Bieniemy interviewed for head-coaching jobs with nearly half the league. He has not yet been requested for an interview, or at least no requests have been reported, during this cycle.

Ben Johnson, Lions offensive coordinator

Johnson has been the Lions offensive coordinator for the past two seasons. The Lions rank fourth in points per game and fifth in EPA per play. After Sean McVay and the Rams gave up on Jared Goff in the deal that netted them Matthew Stafford, Goff has looked much better in Johnson’s system. Over the past two seasons, Goff ranks sixth in EPA per dropback.

Johnson is among the hottest coaches in this cycle. He has already been requested for interviews by the Chargers, Commanders, Panthers and Titans, after taking two interviews last year and turning down a third. The Lions host the Rams on Sunday night.

Todd Monken, Ravens offensive coordinator

Monken, 57, returned to the NFL this season after three years calling plays at Georgia. Baltimore’s offense ranked fourth in scoring and ninth in EPA per play this year, and quarterback Lamar Jackson is the odds-on favorite to win the MVP award for the second time. The Chargers and Panthers have requested interviews with Monken, whose Ravens have a bye in the first round of the playoffs.

Potential first-time coaches (defense)

Ejiro Evero, Panthers defensive coordinator

Evero, 43, was Denver’s defensive coordinator under Nathaniel Hackett in 2022 before taking over the Panthers defense this season. The Broncos defense under Evero was basically the team’s only bright spot. The unit ranked seventh in EPA per play and 14th in scoring despite getting very little from the offense.

This year’s Panthers were no different — Carolina had one of the league’s worst scoring offenses, and the head coach was again fired during the season — though Evero’s unit wasn’t as equipped to overcome those circumstances. Still, the Panthers are considering Evero for their head-coaching vacancy, and they’ve blocked the Jaguars from interviewing him for their defensive coordinator opening.

Mike Macdonald, Ravens defensive coordinator

In 2022, the Ravens had one of the best defenses in the league under Macdonald. This season, they had the best defense, at least by points per drive (they ranked third in EPA). Seattle saw that firsthand in a 37-3 loss in Week 9. Macdonald, 36, might be honored as the league’s best assistant coach and has already been requested for interviews by the Commanders, Panthers and Titans.

Other options

  • Los Angeles Rams DC Raheem Morris
  • Washington Huskies HC Kalen DeBoer
  • Detroit Lions DC Aaron Glenn
  • Las Vegas Raiders DC Patrick Graham
  • Cincinnati Bengals DC Lou Anarumo

(Photos of Jim Harbaugh, left, Dan Quinn and Dave Canales: Leslie Plaza Johnson, Andy Lewis, David Berding / Icon Sportswire via Getty Images)
